***REMOVED*** Proteomic and Phosphoproteomic Analysis

Brett Engelmann(Integrative Proteomics)

March 15th, 2019

Overview

The purpose of this project is to Discern differences in signaling between normal fibroblasts vs.their transformed cancer-associated counterparts in an effort to articulate underpinning biology that may be exploited for pharmaceutical intervention. Human donor fibroblasts from two normal and two cancer-associated breast tissues were cultured at ABR to approximately 15 million cells per donor, scraped from cell culture dish with Accutase containing 1x PhosSTOP, then divided into three aliquots of 5 million cells. Cells were pelleted and washed twice with 1x PhosSTOP in PBS. Final cell pellets were flash frozen and kept at -80 C until arriving at MS Bioworks for phosphoproteomics sample workup. Replicates can be considered technical, in that they incompass repeated, separate applications of the phosphoproteomic enrichment and LC-MS protocol. 12 proteomic and 12 phosphoproteomic samples were processed with 4 and 2 hour RP-HPLC gradients respectively.

These data were processed with maxquant/andromeda (V 1.6.0.16) on 2/1/19 using a human coding sequence (CCDS) ~35,000 sequences) Homo_sapiens.GRCh38.84.pep.all.parsedCCDS.fa database retrieved from Ensembl in May of 2016. A common contaminants list was appended to this FASTA to facilitate their exclusion. The mq parameters file mqpar2_4_19 in this directory has all the MQ parameter choices.

Some key MaxQuant processing parameters:

  • FixedMod = Carbamidomethyl
  • VarMod = Oxidation(M); Acetyl (Protein N-term); Phospho (STY) (for appropriate samples)
  • PSM/Protein/Site FDR = .01 using reverted database as decoys
  • The match-between-runs (MBR) feature was enabled
  • Label free quantification (MQ-LFQ) on XICs was employed

Below I analyze the data from the project. Specifically, I assess coverage and quality, transform and normalize the data, perform EDA, impute, and batch effect correct the data. Then, I construct the proper statistical models for differential phosphorylation analysis. Then, I perform a series of enrichment analyses on the data using appropriate ontologies. Finally, the results are exported in a format suitable for web-application deployment.

Phosphosite Data Types

MQ outputs a Phospho (STY)Sites summary table that gives all sites within a protein that are identified. Singly, doubly, and triply phosphorylated peptides that map/localize to this site are quantified. Class 1 sites (C1) are sites with median localiztion probability ~.95 and minimum localization probability of .75.

Model Definition

We would like to identify differentially expressed proteins and differentially phosphorylated peptides across donors.

All models are wrong but some are useful - George Box

Ideally, a single linear mixed-effects model would be used to test for differences between normal and cancer associated fibroblasts. I have tried this and, due to the underpowered design (their are only two samples in each condition), I do not find and differential expression with such a model. Therefore, I have moved forward with a model to test for differences across donors.

This model will be applied on the:

  • proteome
  • phosphoproteome
  • proteome normalized phosphoproteome

Model

Linear regression model with surrogate variables (estimated separately) added as covariates:

\[Y_{jk} = Donor_{j} + SV_l + {\epsilon}_{jk}: j=3,4,6,8; k = 1,2,3; l=1,...,N\] where \(Y_{jk}\) is logged protein, phosphosite, or protein-normalized-phosphosite intensity of technical replicate k from firbroblast donor j. \(Donor_{j}\) is the estimated effect from donor j and \(SV_k\) is the estimated fixed effect from a covariate surrogate variable l identified from the data (see below).

Heuristic

For a protein/phosphopeptide to be analyzed it needs to be observed at least once per donor.

3024 phosphopeptides and 1419 protein groups satisfy either of the above conditions. The MedianQuantiledImputed.passed and MedianQuantiledProteinImputed.passed data frames are used for modeling. The corresponding binary data frames have the logical results of the heuristic test associated with each peptide. The peptides that do not pass the test have been removed.

on hold

Latent variation correction with SVA

Here I attempt to correct for unwanted latent sources of variation with surrogate variable analysis (SVA), a popular form of weighted factor analysis. I have protected donor (see section above for more details on each model) with a fixed effects regression model. Here I use the complete cases from each molecular phenotype.

Proteome

Here I work with the MedianQuantiledProteinCompleteCases dataframe to identifiy factors not associated with donor.

## Iteration (out of 5 ):1  2  3  4  5

2 surrogate variables were identified. Below are the PCA plots before and after regressing away the surrogate variables on the 904 complete cases. After surrogate variable regression, the effect of the one outlier sample is addressed and the donors cluster together. In both cases PC1 is seems to be explained by the difference between donor 3 and the other donors.

Phosphoproteome

Here I work with the 1017 phosphosite intensities from the MedianQuantiledCompleteCases dataframe to identifiy factors not associated with donor.

## Iteration (out of 5 ):1  2  3  4  5

Again, 2 surrogate variables were identified. Below are the PCA plots before and after regressing away the surrogate variables on the 1017 complete cases. After surrogate variable regression, the donors cluster a bit closer together. In both cases PC1 is seems to be explained by the difference between donor 3 and the other donors (consistent with the proteomic data).

Inference

Differential protein expression and phosphorylation is performed within the limma framework. In all cases eBayes is run with robust=TRUE to deal with hypervariable genes.

Proteome

1419 proteins were ultimately fit to the model (see Model Definition above). The two SVs identified above were included as covariates. Six contrasts (comparisons between donors) were examined.

## [1] TRUE

A few EDA plots show no obvious artifacts associated with this analysis. However, the plot of the model fit residuals vs average log expression (last plot) indicates an intensity dependent trend, that could lead to protein expression dependent diffexp calls. This trend was accounted for in limma by fitting with a prior variance (eBayes trend=TRUE) intensity distribution trend estimated by the average log expression and therefore any bias related to protein expression should be driven by biology.

Enrichment Analysis

Enrichment analysis is performed on protein and phospho data. Reactome, GO(bp,mf,cc, slim) and CORUM are applied. Within each ontology, every annotation must be represented at least three times in the dataset to be considered for enrichment analysis.

Proteome

Phosphoproteome

Data Export

Exported:

  1. The median, quantile normalized, imputed (across all samples) and SV regressed, protein and phosphopeptide XICs
  2. The MS meta data and other identifiers associated with each protein and site
  3. A binary matrix indicating if a data point was measured (1) or imputed (0) for protein and phosphosites
  4. Study meta data
  5. Inference test results
  6. Enrichment analysis results and indices

Note that for phoshoproteome data, numbers 1 and 2 are combined into a single table SiteTableCombined. This SiteTableCombined table has a dupidmult column for duplicated quantifications that account for doubly or triply phosphorylated peptides mapping to mulitple sites. Numbers 3 and 4 are single tables. 4 may or may not be available. 5 and 6 are exported in binary format that I will use for package construction. All of this data will be used with the the app.

note that multiply phosphorylated peptides are only represented once and therefore in such cases the site of modification is not unique

The key for annotation mergining is the ENSP identifier in the protein column. HGNC symbols that map to protein ENSPs are sourced from biomart ensembl84 database. Currently, Mark Ciaccios netmed database is also being used. note that some proteins do not have mapped HGNC symbols
